Picture a tree where the **root is the empty string** and every edge you walk appends one character. Any node you stand on *is* a prefix — the one spelled by the path from the root. Insert `"app"`, `"apt"`, and `"cap"` and the shared `"ap"` prefix is stored **once**; the two words split only at the last letter.

[[fig:m07-trie-paths]]

> [!ANALOGY]
> A Trie is a phone-menu tree: "press *a*, then *p*…". Every caller who wants a word starting with `ap` walks the *same* first two menu levels. The tree never stores `"app"` and `"apt"` separately up to the split — it stores the shared road once and forks at the end.

Two design decisions define the node:

1. **Children storage.** A fixed array `child[26]` for lowercase letters (fast, cache-friendly), or an `unordered_map<char, TrieNode*>` when the alphabet is large or unknown. In OAs it's almost always the array.
2. **The `isEnd` flag.** Every node is a *prefix*, but only some prefixes are *words*. `isEnd = true` marks "a real inserted word terminates exactly here." This one boolean is the difference between `search` and `startsWith`.

Here is the template to burn into muscle memory:

```cpp
struct TrieNode {
    TrieNode* child[26] = {};   // child[c] == nullptr means no edge for letter c
    bool isEnd = false;         // true if a word ends exactly here
    // Optional extras used by harder problems:
    // int passCount = 0;       // how many words pass through this node (prefix count)
    // int endCount  = 0;       // how many words end here (for duplicates)
};

struct Trie {
    TrieNode* root = new TrieNode();

    void insert(const string& w) {
        TrieNode* cur = root;
        for (char ch : w) {
            int c = ch - 'a';
            if (!cur->child[c]) cur->child[c] = new TrieNode();
            cur = cur->child[c];
            // cur->passCount++;   // if you need prefix counts
        }
        cur->isEnd = true;
    }

    // exact word present?
    bool search(const string& w) {
        TrieNode* cur = walk(w);
        return cur && cur->isEnd;
    }

    // any word with this prefix?
    bool startsWith(const string& p) {
        return walk(p) != nullptr;
    }

private:
    // follow the path for s; return the node it ends at, or nullptr if it breaks
    TrieNode* walk(const string& s) {
        TrieNode* cur = root;
        for (char ch : s) {
            int c = ch - 'a';
            if (!cur->child[c]) return nullptr;
            cur = cur->child[c];
        }
        return cur;
    }
};
```

Notice the shape: **one private `walk` helper**, and both public queries are one-liners on top of it. That factoring is what makes the template hard to get wrong under time pressure.

> [!EXAMPLE]
> Insert `"apple"` only. Now trace: `search("app")` → `walk` reaches the `p` node fine, but `isEnd` there is **false** → returns `false`. `startsWith("app")` → the node exists → `true`. `search("apple")` → node exists *and* `isEnd` is true → `true`. If your implementation gives any other trio of answers, you have the classic bug.

**Complexity.** `insert`, `search`, and `startsWith` are all $O(L)$ where $L$ is the string's length — the alphabet size is a constant factor, not part of the input. Space is $O(\text{total characters} \times 26)$ in the worst case, because each node carries the full child array.

> [!PITFALL]
> The single most common Trie bug: returning `walk(w) != nullptr` from `search`. That makes `search("app")` return true after inserting only `"apple"` — you've silently turned `search` into `startsWith`. Test both calls explicitly before submitting.

Here's the variant that looks nothing like strings but is the same data structure: treat every integer as a **30-bit string of 0s and 1s, most-significant bit first**, and insert it into a Trie with two children per node. You've never needed this before — it's the standard weapon for "maximum XOR of a pair" problems, and it shows up in hard OA sets.

Why MSB-first matters: XOR is decided bit by bit, and **a higher bit outweighs all lower bits combined** ($2^b > 2^{b-1} + \dots + 1$). So to maximize `x XOR y`, walk down from the top bit and greedily steer toward the child holding the **opposite** of `x`'s bit — every time you succeed, you lock in $2^b$ and nothing below can make you regret it.

[[fig:m07-bit-greedy]]

```cpp
struct BitTrie {
    BitTrie* child[2] = {};     // child[0] and child[1] for bit 0 / bit 1
};

const int BITS = 30;            // enough for values < ~1e9; use 31/32 for larger

void insert(BitTrie* root, int x) {
    BitTrie* cur = root;
    for (int b = BITS; b >= 0; --b) {           // MOST significant bit first
        int bit = (x >> b) & 1;
        if (!cur->child[bit]) cur->child[bit] = new BitTrie();
        cur = cur->child[bit];
    }
}

// max XOR of x with any number already inserted
int queryMaxXor(BitTrie* root, int x) {
    BitTrie* cur = root;
    int res = 0;
    for (int b = BITS; b >= 0; --b) {
        int bit = (x >> b) & 1;
        int want = bit ^ 1;                     // greedily try the OPPOSITE bit
        if (cur->child[want]) { res |= (1 << b); cur = cur->child[want]; }
        else                    cur = cur->child[bit];
    }
    return res;
}
```

> [!KEY]
> The greedy is *provably* optimal only because you process bits **high to low**. Securing bit $b$ is worth more than every bit below it combined, so grabbing the opposite bit when it exists can never be a mistake.

> [!PITFALL]
> Two ways this template dies: (1) iterating bits **LSB-first** — the trie levels no longer correspond to the bits you're testing and the greedy priority inverts; (2) choosing a bit width too small for the max value. Use 30 bits for values under $\sim 10^9$, and be careful with the sign bit if values can use all 32 bits.

deepdives.answer:
**Why the naive approach dies.** The obvious plan is to run Word Search I once per word. For $W$ words each doing a full-board DFS, that's $O(W \times \text{cells} \times 4^{\text{maxLen}})$. With hundreds of words it's hopeless — and notice *why* it's wasteful: words sharing a prefix (`"oath"`, `"oats"`) force you to redo the exact same board exploration for the shared letters.

> [!INTUITION]
> Flip the loop inside-out. Instead of "for each word, search the board," do **one DFS over the board, walking the Trie in lockstep**. The Trie has already merged every shared prefix, so a single board path checks *all* words with that prefix simultaneously. The instant the current board letter has no matching Trie child, you stop — and that one check kills an entire family of words at once.

[[fig:m07-board-lockstep]]

**The trick, step by step.**

1. Insert all words into a Trie, storing the **full word on the terminal node** (`node->word`) so you never reconstruct it from the path.
2. DFS from every cell, carrying the current Trie node alongside the board position. Step to a neighbor only if `node->child[letter]` exists.
3. When you land on a node whose `word` is non-empty, record it and **clear it** (`node->word = ""`) — automatic deduplication, no set needed.
4. Mark cells visited by temporarily overwriting the board char with `'#'`, and restore it on backtrack.
5. Optional but powerful: after collecting a word, **prune leaf Trie nodes** with no children, so future paths die even faster.

```cpp
void dfs(vector<vector<char>>& b, int i, int j, TrieNode* node, vector<string>& out) {
    char ch = b[i][j];
    if (ch == '#' || !node->child[ch - 'a']) return;   // wall or no matching word
    node = node->child[ch - 'a'];
    if (!node->word.empty()) {                          // found a whole word
        out.push_back(node->word);
        node->word.clear();                             // dedupe: never emit twice
    }
    b[i][j] = '#';                                      // mark visited
    int dx[] = {0,0,1,-1}, dy[] = {1,-1,0,0};
    for (int d = 0; d < 4; ++d) {
        int ni = i + dx[d], nj = j + dy[d];
        if (ni >= 0 && ni < b.size() && nj >= 0 && nj < b[0].size())
            dfs(b, ni, nj, node, out);
    }
    b[i][j] = ch;                                       // restore (backtrack)
}
```

**Complexity.** Roughly $O(\text{cells} \times 4 \times 3^{\text{maxLen}-1})$ in the worst case — after the first step each cell has at most 3 unvisited neighbors — but Trie pruning makes it far faster in practice because dead prefixes are cut instantly. Space is $O(\text{total letters in all words})$ for the Trie.

**What generalizes.** "Merge many patterns into one structure, then run the expensive search **once**, pruning against the structure" — the same idea powers multi-pattern matching everywhere. And the two classic bugs to check before submitting: restore `b[i][j]`, clear `node->word`.

**Why the naive approach dies.** Checking all pairs is $O(n^2)$ — fine at $n = 2000$, dead at the $n = 2 \times 10^5$ that OAs love: that's $4 \times 10^{10}$ operations.

> [!KEY]
> XOR is decided **bit by bit, most-significant first**, and a set bit at position $b$ contributes $2^b$ — more than *all lower bits combined*. So a greedy that walks from the top bit and grabs "the opposite of my bit, if any inserted number has it" is provably optimal: securing a high bit can never be regretted, no matter what happens below.

**The algorithm.**

1. Insert every number into a **binary trie**, MSB → LSB, at a fixed depth (30 bits covers values under $\sim 10^9$).
2. For each `x`, walk down from the root. At bit $b$, try the child holding the **opposite** of `x`'s bit — if it exists, take it and OR $2^b$ into the running answer; otherwise you're forced down the same-bit child and that bit of the answer stays 0.
3. The answer is the max over all `x` of that query.

[[fig:m07-bit-greedy]]

```cpp
struct BitTrie {
    BitTrie* child[2] = {};     // child[0] and child[1] for bit 0 / bit 1
};

const int BITS = 30;            // enough for values < ~1e9; use 31/32 for larger

void insert(BitTrie* root, int x) {
    BitTrie* cur = root;
    for (int b = BITS; b >= 0; --b) {           // MOST significant bit first
        int bit = (x >> b) & 1;
        if (!cur->child[bit]) cur->child[bit] = new BitTrie();
        cur = cur->child[bit];
    }
}

// max XOR of x with any number already inserted
int queryMaxXor(BitTrie* root, int x) {
    BitTrie* cur = root;
    int res = 0;
    for (int b = BITS; b >= 0; --b) {
        int bit = (x >> b) & 1;
        int want = bit ^ 1;                     // greedily try the OPPOSITE bit
        if (cur->child[want]) { res |= (1 << b); cur = cur->child[want]; }
        else                    cur = cur->child[bit];
    }
    return res;
}
```

**Complexity.** $O(n \times \text{BITS})$ — about $30n$ operations, effectively linear. Space is $O(n \times \text{BITS})$ for the trie nodes.

**The Hard follow-up** (*Maximum XOR With an Element From Array*): each query `(x, limit)` restricts you to elements $\le$ `limit`. The trick is to go **offline**: sort the queries by limit and the array by value, then sweep — insert numbers into the trie only as the limit passes them, answering each query against a trie that contains *exactly* the eligible elements. This "sort queries + monotonic insertion pointer" pattern is worth recognizing on its own; it converts per-query filtering into one linear pass.

**Why it's tricky.** The plain `walk` helper breaks the instant it meets `.` — there is no single child to follow. A hashset of whole words can't help either, because `.` means the query matches a whole *family* of words. You need to explore **all** possibilities, but only at the wildcard positions.

> [!INTUITION]
> Turn `walk` into a **DFS**. On a normal character, descend the one matching child (fail fast if it's null — that's most of your speed). On `.`, fan out into **every non-null child** and recurse; the search succeeds if *any* branch reaches the end of the query on an `isEnd` node. The Trie keeps the fan-out cheap because in real data most of the 26 children don't exist.

[[fig:m07-wildcard-branch]]

```cpp
bool dfs(TrieNode* node, const string& w, int i) {
    if (!node) return false;
    if (i == w.size()) return node->isEnd;
    char ch = w[i];
    if (ch == '.') {                             // wildcard: try every child
        for (int c = 0; c < 26; ++c)
            if (node->child[c] && dfs(node->child[c], w, i + 1)) return true;
        return false;
    }
    return dfs(node->child[ch - 'a'], w, i + 1); // fixed letter: one path
}
```

Note the two base cases, in order: a null node means the path broke (`false`); reaching the end of the query means the answer is exactly `node->isEnd` — not `true`! Reaching a *prefix* of a stored word is not a match.

**Complexity.** A no-wildcard search is $O(L)$. The theoretical worst case with all dots is $O(26^L)$, but actual inputs branch rarely, so it runs fast in practice. Space is just the Trie.

**What generalizes.** "Deterministic walk + controlled branching at uncertainty points" is the skeleton of every Trie-DFS hybrid — Word Search II branches on board neighbors, this problem branches on `.`, regex-lite matchers branch on character classes. Master this one and the family opens up.

**Why naive fails.** For each word, trying every split into two halves recursively explodes; and hashing every substring `s[i..j]` against a set costs $O(L^2)$ substring constructions *per word*, each $O(L)$ to hash — the constants pile up fast at $10^4$ words.

> [!KEY]
> Two observations tame it. First, a concatenated word is strictly **longer than its parts** — so process words shortest-first, and each word only needs to be built from words already inserted. Second, "can the prefix of length $k$ be split into dictionary words?" is a classic **Word-Break DP**, and a Trie answers "which dictionary words start at position $i$?" with **one downward walk** instead of one hash lookup per substring.

**The algorithm.**

1. Sort the words by length, ascending.
2. For each word `s`: run `dp[k]` = "the prefix `s[0..k)` splits into inserted dictionary words," with `dp[0] = true`. To fill it, from every reachable position `i` walk the Trie along `s[i..]`; every time you pass a node with `isEnd`, mark `dp[j+1] = true` for that end position `j`.
3. The word qualifies if `dp[len]` is true using **at least two** pieces — since the word itself isn't inserted yet when tested (shortest-first order), any successful split automatically uses other words.
4. Insert `s` into the Trie and move on.

```cpp
struct TrieNode {
    TrieNode* child[26] = {};
    bool isEnd = false;
};

class Solution {
    TrieNode* root = new TrieNode();

    void insert(const string& w) {
        TrieNode* cur = root;
        for (char ch : w) {
            int c = ch - 'a';
            if (!cur->child[c]) cur->child[c] = new TrieNode();
            cur = cur->child[c];
        }
        cur->isEnd = true;
    }

    bool canForm(const string& s) {
        int n = s.size();
        if (n == 0) return false;
        vector<char> dp(n + 1, false);
        dp[0] = true;                       // empty prefix splits trivially
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            if (!dp[i]) continue;           // position i unreachable
            TrieNode* cur = root;
            for (int j = i; j < n; ++j) {   // one walk enumerates all words at i
                int c = s[j] - 'a';
                if (!cur->child[c]) break;  // no dictionary word continues
                cur = cur->child[c];
                if (cur->isEnd) dp[j + 1] = true;
            }
        }
        return dp[n];
    }

public:
    vector<string> findAllConcatenatedWordsInADict(vector<string>& words) {
        sort(words.begin(), words.end(),
             [](const string& a, const string& b) { return a.size() < b.size(); });
        vector<string> res;
        for (const string& w : words) {
            if (canForm(w)) res.push_back(w);   // built ONLY from shorter words
            insert(w);                          // insert AFTER testing
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

The "insert **after** testing" line is what enforces the *at least two other words* rule — when `canForm(w)` runs, `w` itself isn't in the Trie, so any successful split necessarily uses other (shorter) words, and a single-piece "split" is impossible.

**Complexity.** About $O(n \times L^2)$ for $n$ words of length up to $L$ — for each word, each start position launches one Trie walk of at most $L$ steps. The Trie replaces per-substring hashing with a clean pointer walk, a much smaller constant. Space is the Trie: $O(\text{total characters} \times 26)$.

**What generalizes.** Word Break, Word Break II, and this problem are one family: **DP over cut positions, with a Trie (or hashset) certifying pieces**. Whenever a string must be tiled by dictionary units, reach for this exact skeleton.
